{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507326"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2621"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2621"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.01,0.03,0.67,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59541"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2621"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"3338"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5067"},{"type":"tags","id":"9590"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43195"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59541"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of routine blood tests. She has no symptoms. She has a medical history of congestive heart failure, hypertension, osteoporosis and mild Alzheimer\u0027s disease. Her medications include perindopril, hydrochlorothiazide, metoprolol extended-release, risedronate, donepezil and calcium/vitamin D supplements. She has not changed her medications or diet recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Blood tests reveal serum calcium 2.8 mmol/L (2.1-2.6) and sodium 132 mmol/L (135-145).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the hypercalcaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Risedronate","Metoprolol","Perindopril","Hydrochlorothiazide","Donepezil"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis elderly woman presents with asymptomatic hypercalcaemia and hyponatraemia on routine blood tests. Among her medications, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause. Thiazide diuretics increase calcium reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule through increased activity of the basal sodium-calcium exchanger. They also cause hyponatraemia by blocking sodium chloride reabsorption and impairing the kidney\u0027s diluting capacity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisedronate\u003C/strong\u003E is a bisphosphonate that decreases serum calcium by inhibiting osteoclast activity. It typically causes hypocalcaemia rather than hypercalcaemia, which is why calcium and vitamin D supplementation is usually co-prescribed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-blocker that has no direct effects on calcium homeostasis. While it is useful in treating hypertension and heart failure, it does not affect serum calcium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, can affect sodium and potassium levels but does not directly influence calcium metabolism. It works primarily by inhibiting the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDonepezil\u003C/strong\u003E is an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor used in Alzheimer\u0027s disease. It has no known effects on calcium or other electrolyte levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thiazide diuretics commonly cause hypercalcaemia by increasing calcium reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule","Thiazide diuretics frequently cause hyponatraemia through decreased sodium reabsorption and impaired diluting capacity","Bisphosphonates can cause hypocalcaemia"],"references":["Griebeler ML, Kearns AE, Ryu E, Trappa P, Hathcock MA, Melton LJ, Wermers RA. Thiazide-Associated Hypercalcemia: Incidence and Association With Primary Hyperparathyroidism Over Two Decades. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2016;101(3):1166-1173. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26751196/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2621"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44950"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T12:38:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-08T12:39:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2621"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59541"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i